- 'Stars of the show shining the brightest' is a metaphor for the algorithms that have achieved the highest convergence in their respective categories.

- 'Shining stars' refers to users with the best performance in their algorithm runs;
- 'Highest level of convergence' refers to the maximum convergence metric value;
- The convergence metric is a measure of how well the algorithm is performing, with higher values indicating better performance.

- "Flowers" and "garden" are metaphors for algorithms and the environment in which they are run;
- "Gardeners" and "tended to" are metaphors for users and the process of running algorithms;
- "Watered" and "blooming" are metaphors for the number of runs and successful executions of algorithms;
- "Health of the plant" is a metaphor for the convergence metric, indicating how well the algorithm is performing.

- 'Average convergence' is a metric that indicates how well the algorithm is converging towards an optimal solution;
- 'Generation 4000' refers to the 4000th iteration of the algorithm run;
- 'Completed runs' are those runs that have successfully finished without errors or interruptions.

- "Most stellar performance" refers to the highest convergence metric;
